MQTT vs HTTP Comparison
| Feature                  | MQTT                                                       | HTTP                                      |
| ------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| Architecture Pattern     | Publish/Subscribe                                          | Client/Server                             |
| Data Transfer Model      | Broker-based messaging                                     | Request and Response                      |
| Power Consumption        | Low                                                        | High                                      |
| Latency                  | Very Low                                                   | Higher than MQTT                          |
| IoT Suitability          | Excellent for IoT devices due to lightweight communication | Better for web applications and REST APIs |
| Security                 | Supports TLS/SSL, authentication, access control           | Supports HTTPS (SSL/TLS), authentication  |

Which protocol is better for a 1000-node Smart Agriculture deployment?

For a smart agriculture system with around 1000 sensor nodes, MQTT is the preferred protocol.

Reasons:

It consumes very little bandwidth.
It requires less power, increasing battery life.
It provides fast communication with low latency.
A single MQTT broker can efficiently handle thousands of devices.
Only subscribed devices receive the required data, reducing unnecessary network traffic.
It is reliable even on unstable or low-bandwidth networks.

Therefore, MQTT is more suitable than HTTP for large-scale IoT deployments such as smart agriculture.
